<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[813,1452,1773,1958]" lastBlockId="2.[820,1459,174,358]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,937,1773,1797]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vari &amp; Melo &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2016" box="[973,1152,1774,1798]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Protocheirodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[973,1152,1774,1798]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Protocheirodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses the four synapomorphies proposed for the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1915" box="[1235,1406,1806,1830]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cheirodontinae">Cheirodontinae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Malabarba" box="[813,1011,1838,1862]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="193 - 233" refId="ref5103" refString="Malabarba, L. R. 1998. Monophyly of the Cheirodontinae, characters and major clades (Ostariophysi: Characidae). Pp. 193 - 233. In: Malabarba, L. R., R. E. Reis, R. P. Vari, Z. M. S. Lucena &amp; C. A. S. Lucena (Orgs.). Phylogeny and classification of Neotropical fishes. Porto Alegre, Edipucrs." type="book chapter" year="1998">Malabarba (1998)</bibRefCitation>
: 1) the presence of a pseudotympanum, a hiatus in the body wall musculature lateral to at least a portion of the anterior chamber of the swimbladder; 2) the lack of a dark humeral spot; 3) the possession of pedunculate dentition; and 4) the presence of only a single row of regularly arranged premaxillary teeth. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vari &amp; Melo &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2016" box="[601,775,206,230]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Protocheirodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[601,775,206,230]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Protocheirodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other genera of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1915" box="[553,724,238,262]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cheirodontinae">Cheirodontinae</taxonomicName>
and indeed members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[394,557,270,294]" class="Actinopterygii" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Characiformes</taxonomicName>
by the unique form of the swimbladder which has a smaller rotund anterior chamber and the posteriorly chamber elaborated into two vertically elongate, side by side, slightly inclined chambers. These modifications yield a unique overall pi (π)-shaped structure (Vari, 1978) (
<figureCitation box="[1207,1275,238,262]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,175,1504,1528]" captionTargetBox="[136,1459,404,1489]" captionTargetId="figure-108@2.[136,1459,404,1489]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Protocheirodon pi, (A) CAS 41749, 29.5 mm SL; Colombia, Amazonas, Isla de Santa Sofia II, ca. 20 mi (= 32 km) NW of Leticia; (B) live specimen from aquarium without locality information. Scale bar = 5 mm. Photo credits: (A) Sandra Raredon (USNM) and (B) Martin and Peter Hoffmann." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4974899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4974899/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). This trenchant difference 
<emphasis box="[941,1012,271,294]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">versus</emphasis>
other cheirodontins is supplemented by a diagnostic combination of meristic, morphometric and details of pigmentation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4974899" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4974899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4974899/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" startId="2.[136,175,1504,1528]" targetBox="[136,1459,404,1489]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1459,1504,1593]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,209,1504,1528]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[216,415,1505,1529]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vari &amp; Melo &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2016" box="[216,387,1505,1529]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Protocheirodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Protocheirodon</taxonomicName>
pi
</emphasis>
, (A) CAS 41749, 29.5 mm SL; Colombia, Amazonas, Isla de Santa Sofia II, 
<emphasis box="[1242,1275,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">ca.</emphasis>
20 mi (= 32 km) NW of Leticia; (B) live specimen from aquarium without locality information. Scale bar = 5 mm. Photo credits: (A) Sandra Raredon (USNM) and (B) Martin and Peter Hoffmann.
</paragraph>
